title: For Sale:  Finn or Finnish Mosin M24 Lotta's rifle
postcontent:
Hi, what we have here is a Finnish M24 that has seen some use.

The rifle exudes history from stock to finish.

It is a very nice example of the "Lotta" rifle, the only real detractor from this rifle is that it has a mismatched serialized bolt, which is fairly common place among Mosins.

This one is not counterbored and has it's original stock finish and bluing, plenty of rifling left and a nice tight muzzle with what looks to be the original crown. 

There are a few (dime size?) A and W stamps (a couple of which actually look raised) on this stock, it also has a wooden dow type (pencil sized) plug on the bottom where an Austrian type swivel would/might have been screwed in at one time.

Either way the Russian M91 butt part of the stock was later reused and fingerspliced by the "Finn's" into what it is now.

Please feel free to ask questions and I'll answer what I can, other great information can be found on Vic Thomas's site with this link.

http://mosinnagant.net/finland/M24-Rifle.asp

I would  like $400.00 for this one in a face to face sale in the Richmond, Henrico, Mechanicsville area.


Sling and loops are not part of this sale.

As stated in my other listings I have not fired this one and I am only selling this and other pieces to purchase another equally nice rifle that is not already in my collection.

Sorry, I didn't notice until after dark that only a few of my pictures were presentable, so this is what I have.

Don't miss out on this nice piece, with no shipping charges or auction hassles and anxiety. 

Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale/Trade:  SITES Spectre HC 9mm
postcontent:
This listing is for a very rare SITES Spectre HC Semi-Automatic 9mm pistol. This gun has never been fired, finish is excellent, comes with all original paperwork.  Was purchased in early 90`s and kept in my safe.  It is just a little over 14 inches in length, and comes with original 30 round clip

 The Spectre is an Italian submachine gun that was produced by the SITES factory in Turin. It was designed by Roberto Teppa and Claudio Gritti in the mid-1980s. Production in Italy ceased in the year 1997, with the closure of SITES, but proceeded in very small numbers in Switzerland through Greco Sport S.A., a company founded by one of the designers of the Spectre, Claudio Gritti, until 2001. During the mid 80’s and early 90’s, a limited number made its way to the states via imported by American Arms Inc. The Spectre is used by the Swiss armed forces and by Italian armed forces, and has been exported elsewhere.

The Spectre is a compact and light weapon, designed for instant firepower in close combat at short ranges. The four models have top-folding buttstocks, and were available with or without a forward handgrip ahead of the magazine housing. The largely polymer Spectre has a stamped-steel receiver.

The Spectre is a standard blowback firearm operating from a closed bolt; however it has some unusual features. The barrel shroud completely hides the barrel. The bolt is designed to pump air through the barrel shroud to provide additional cooling. The Spectre is hammer-fired and the trigger group is double action with a decocker. This allows the shooter to safely carry a round in the chamber and fire immediately. As this eliminates the need for cocking prior to shooting no manual safety is provided. Unconventional 30-round capacity, four-column magazine is provided with the Spectre, but it can also use conventional magazines.

postcontent:
This is a 4th Generation Charter Arms Pathfinder manufactured in Shelton, Conn.  It has the stainless cylinder, stainless satin finish, low profile fixed sights, combat grips, exposed hammer, and a smooth trigger pull.  It is chambered for the powerful yet light recoiling .22 WMR round.  Loaded with FMJ this round can penetrate 5" of pine or over 24" of ballistic gelatin.  Loaded with ballistic tipped hunting ammo the bullet will explode 5" after impact.  Stopping power of the .22 Magnum is comparable to .380 ACP, but unlike an automatic pistol a revolver will never jam.  This is the PERFECT CCW for novice shooters who are sensitive to recoil or individuals with arthritis or wrist injuries.  Powerful, reliable, lightweight, and zero recoil.

This pistol is like new in box with papers and everything that came with it.  Only approximately 100 rounds down the pipe.  A few very minor handling / holster marks which are barely noticeable unless you're really looking hard under a strong light.  This gun is really LNIB, but I'll call it "excellent" condition. 

ANY factory or aftermarket Charter Arms grip will fit the Pathfinder (Undercover, Off Duty, Bulldog, etc) if you'd like some wood grips.  Custom grips are frequently available on eBay (there's a set of pearl grips up there right now).  This revolver will fit in ANY J-frame holster.  I recommend the Uncle Mike's Size 3 pocket holster.

Pistol runs fine.  I decided I would prefer another .38 instead.  Selling at a steep discount to fund another purchase.  Not interested in any trades unless you have a Charter Arms DAO or a Taurus 85CH.  Might consider another LCR.  I will accept good quality factory .44 Special ammo as a partial trade (no reloads).

I will include a box of ballistic tipped hunting ammo with this revolver.

Prefer to meet within a reasonable distance of greater Denver area.  CASH ONLY.  WILL NOT SHIP.  No bad guys.

Thanks.

title: For Sale/Trade:  german RSI beretta m1935
postcontent:
this beretta pistol was included in a delivery of 65,000 Beretta M1934/35 pistols delivered to the German wehrmacht Headquarters in Italy between Aug 1944 and Feb, 1945. Those serial # were 534000/599000.
After the 8 September 1943 armistice between Italy and the Allies, the Germans saddled Beretta with three engineers from Germany. Moreover the factory was garrisoned by the waffen ss!!! 'armed security service' Weapons of that time, even the ones produced for the Germans, bore the punch mark 4UT, (Quarto Ufficio tecnico di Controllo Armi e Munizioni--4th Technnical Control Unit...
-an C. Still, in Axis Pistols, page 107, states,
"It is likely that almost all of the 4/UT, ...were used by the German Army". He also includes two other variations in this statement, "1944 dated and blank slide Model 1935".
Ugo Menchini, in Pietro Beretta Le Automatiche, regarding an M1934, page 255, states,
"In late 1940 there appears an oval including the punch mark IVU. It refers to the 4th technical Control Unit of the FAG, where inspection was carried out."
Note that, while they seem to represent the same inspectors, the "IVU" is not the same mark as the "4UT". The IVU would be found on the pre RSI model M1934, and the 4UT would be found on the RSI model M1935.
These are the reasons why I believe that it is likely that all of the 4UT Berettas WERE RSI pistols!! the IVU and the 4UT were the same office, but under Italian management -the IVU, before the surrender of Italy, and German the 4UT, so after september, 8 1943.........

Mussolini was rescued by German paratroopers led by Otto Skorzeny. He was then installed by the Germans as the President of the Italian Social Republic (RSI). The RSI was to be an Italian regime which was to nominally administer the German-occupied northern Italy. As the Milizia Volontaria per la Sicurezza Nazionale (MVSN, also known as "Black Shirts") was disbanded by the terms of the armistice, the Guardia Nazionale Repubblicana was formed on 24 November 1943. The "Guardia Nazionale Repubblicana" was formed out of local police, ex-army, and others still loyal to the fascist cause. 

 Pistol is in near unissued condition with mirror bore , mint! no rust, scuffs, dings,tight action. no import markings! BRINGBACK???? a prime example of strain on axis weapons fabrication late in the war, with tooling and machinery marks throughout, it comes with one extra original period magazine!!!!!!!!
***REDACTED**** 

Will trade for: pps43+ cash or ammo beretta 92fs
